# Enterprise Feature Based Architecture Rule

All business logic must follow a **feature-based architecture**.
Each business domain must be isolated inside `features/`.

Next.js routing stays inside `app/`, but route files must remain thin and only compose feature modules.

Technology stack used in this project:

- Next.js App Router
- TanStack Table (table engine)
- TanStack Form (form engine)
- Shadcn UI (UI layer)
- TailwindCSS
- Server Actions for mutations
- Zod for validation
- Prisma for database access
- Better Auth for authentication
- Lucide Icons for icons

UI must remain **headless, reusable, domain-oriented**.

---

# 1. Feature Module structure:

Each domain must live inside:

`features/[feature-name]/`

Example:

- `features/materials/`
- `features/vendors/`
- `features/uoms/`
- `features/users/`

A feature may contain:

- `actions/` - contains server actions and mutation entry points for the feature
- `components/` - contains feature-owned presentation components and UI blocks
- `hooks/` - contains reusable feature-scoped hooks for UI behavior and state handling
- `lib/` - contains feature-owned mappers, transformers, and helpers
- `repositories/` - contains data access logic and persistence queries for the feature
- `services/` - contains use cases, orchestration, and business rules for the feature
- `schemas/` - contains validation schemas for inputs, forms, filters, and requests
- `table/` - contains TanStack Table configuration and table-specific UI for the feature
- `types/` - contains TypeScript types and interfaces owned by the feature
- `constants/` - contains feature-scoped constants, enums, and static configuration values
- `index.ts` - contains the public export surface for the feature

Each folder must have a clear and limited responsibility.

---

# 2. Pages Must Be Thin

Location:
`app/**/page.tsx`

Purpose:
Page files are route entry points only. They define route structure and delegate feature behavior to feature modules.

Rules:

- Must only compose and render feature components or route-level layout blocks
- Must NOT contain business logic
- Must NOT contain form logic
- Must NOT contain table logic
- Must NOT contain data access logic
- Must NOT contain validation logic
- Must NOT contain repository logic
- Must NOT contain service orchestration
- Should keep logic minimal and route-focused
- Should delegate implementation details to the owning feature
- Should use metadata to set the title and description of the page and import appConfig to get the description

Example:
`app/dashboard/materials/page.tsx`

Allowed:

- rendering feature entry components such as `<MaterialTable />`
- passing `params` and `searchParams` to feature modules
- lightweight route composition
- use metadata to set the title and description of the page and import appConfig to get the description

Example:

```tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: "Materials",
  description: `Materials | ${appConfig.description}`,
};
```

Not allowed:

- defining table columns inside the page
- implementing form state inside the page
- calling repositories directly from the page
- placing business rules inside the page

---

# 3. TanStack Table Usage

Purpose:
TanStack Table must follow feature boundaries. Feature-specific table behavior, configuration, state, and table UI must stay inside the owning feature.

Rules:

- Feature-specific table logic must live inside the owning feature module
- Shared data-table primitives may live in `components/data-table/`
- Only generic and reusable table primitives may be shared
- Feature-owned table files must NOT be placed in shared folders
- Columns, row actions, filters, toolbars, and feature-specific table wrappers should live inside `features/[feature-name]/table/`
- Detailed TanStack Table implementation rules are defined in `.cursor/rules/folder-structure/3-tanstack-table-enterprise.mdc` and `.cursor/rules/folder-structure/4-tanstack-table-ui-conventions.mdc`

---

# 4. TanStack Form Usage

Purpose:
TanStack Form must follow feature boundaries. Feature-specific form composition, form state handling, and form UI must stay inside the owning feature.

Rules:

- Feature-specific form logic must live inside the owning feature module
- Shared form primitives may live in `components/form/`
- Only generic and reusable form primitives may be shared
- Feature-owned form files must NOT be placed in shared folders
- Feature forms, form sections, and feature-specific form hooks should live inside the owning feature, typically under `features/[feature-name]/components/`
- Detailed TanStack Form implementation rules are defined in `.cursor/rules/folder-structure/5-tanstack-form.mdc` and `.cursor/rules/folder-structure/6-tanstack-form-ui-conventions.mdc`

---

# 5. Actions

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/actions/`

Purpose:
Handle **server mutations and server actions**.

Scope:

- create
- update
- delete
- complex server workflows
- other feature-specific actions

Rules:

- Must use `"use server"`
- Must validate input using **schemas**
- Must call **services**
- Must NOT access database directly
- Must NOT contain UI logic

Examples:

- `material-create.action.ts`
- `material-update.action.ts`
- `material-toggle-status.action.ts`
- `material-toggle-status-bulk.action.ts`
- `material-delete.action.ts`
- `material-delete-bulk.action.ts`

---

# 6. Components

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/components/`

Purpose:
Store UI components that belong to a single feature and represent the feature’s presentation layer.

Scope:

- forms
- drawers
- dialogs
- cards
- detail sections
- feature-specific layout blocks
- small presentational widgets specific to the feature

Rules:

- Must contain presentation logic only
- Must NOT contain business logic
- Must NOT contain database access logic
- Must NOT contain repository logic
- Must NOT contain service orchestration logic
- May use hooks for UI state, form state, and interaction state
- May trigger actions from event handlers or form submissions
- May receive processed data through props
- Should remain scoped to the feature
- Must NOT be used as cross-feature shared components
- If a component becomes generic and reusable across multiple features, it must be moved to a shared UI location
- Components specific to TanStack Table must live in `features/[feature-name]/table/`, not in `components/`

Guidelines:

- Prefer small, focused components with clear responsibility
- Separate presentational UI from data loading and domain decision logic
- Keep components easy to compose inside pages, dialogs, forms, and feature sections
- Use Server Components by default when possible
- Use Client Components only when interactivity is required

Examples:

- `MaterialForm.tsx`
- `MaterialCreateDrawer.tsx`
- `MaterialCreateDialog.tsx`
- `MaterialEditDrawer.tsx`
- `MaterialEditDialog.tsx`
- `MaterialStatusBadge.tsx`

---

# 7. Hooks

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/hooks/`

Purpose:
This folder contains reusable feature-specific React hooks for client-side behavior.

Hooks should be used to extract shared UI logic from components, not to store server business logic.

Allowed responsibilities:

- component state orchestration
- form orchestration
- table state orchestration
- modal/drawer state
- filter state
- search param synchronization
- action pending/error handling on the client

Disallowed responsibilities:

- database access
- Prisma calls
- repository logic
- server-only service logic
- domain mutation logic that should live in actions/services

Rules:

- Hooks must belong to one feature only
- Keep hooks focused and composable
- Do not create hooks without a real reuse or complexity reason
- Hooks may invoke server actions from client components

Examples:

- `use-material-form.ts`
- `use-material-form-defaults.ts`
- `use-material-form-options.ts`

---

# 8. Services

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/services/`

Purpose:
Services contain business rules, domain constraints, and feature-level orchestration.

Typical scope:

- business rules
- domain constraints
- orchestration across repositories
- transactional application flow
- feature-specific use cases

Rules:

- Must NOT contain UI logic
- Must NOT depend on React
- Must NOT define schema validation
- May enforce business validation and domain rules
- Should call repositories for data access
- May coordinate multiple repositories

Examples:

- `material-create.service.ts`
- `material-update.service.ts`
- `material-toggle-status.service.ts`
- `material-toggle-status-bulk.service.ts`
- `material-delete.service.ts`
- `material-delete-bulk.service.ts`
- `material-get-by-id.service.ts`
- `material-get-list.service.ts`

---

# 9. Repositories

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/repositories/`

Purpose:
Repositories contain Prisma queries and persistence logic for the owning feature.

Typical scope:

- Prisma queries
- create/update/delete persistence operations
- filtering, sorting, and pagination queries
- low-level database access
- transaction-aware persistence operations

Rules:

- Must contain persistence logic only
- Must NOT contain business rules
- Must NOT contain UI logic
- Must NOT depend on React
- Must NOT call actions
- Must NOT call services

Examples:

- `material-list.repository.ts`
- `material-update.repository.ts`
- `material-get-by-id.repository.ts`
- `material-get-list.repository.ts`
- `material-delete.repository.ts`
- `material-delete-bulk.repository.ts`
- `material-toggle-status.repository.ts`
- `material-toggle-status-bulk.repository.ts`

Example usage:
`prisma.mdMaterial.create()`

---

# 10. Schemas

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/schemas/`

Purpose:
Schemas define runtime validation for inputs owned by a feature.

Preferred library:
Zod

Allowed scope:

- form input validation
- server action payload validation
- filter/search param validation
- bulk action validation
- import/export row validation
- safe input coercion and transformation

Rules:

- Must contain validation concerns only
- Must NOT contain UI logic
- Must NOT contain database access
- Must NOT contain business orchestration
- May use `refine`, `superRefine`, `transform`, and `coerce`
- Must NOT enforce business rules that require database state

Examples:

- `material-filter.schema.ts`
- `material-create.schema.ts`
- `material-update.schema.ts`
- `material-delete.schema.ts`
- `material-import.schema.ts`

---

# 11. Types

Location:
`features/[feature-name]/types/`

Purpose:
Types define compile-time contracts for the owning feature.

Allowed scope:

- domain types
- DTO types
- table row types
- form value types
- filter value types
- action result types
- option types
- view model types

Rules:

- Must NOT contain runtime logic
- Must NOT contain business logic
- Must NOT contain UI logic
- May be used by actions, services, repositories, hooks, and components
- Prefer inferring input types from schemas when possible
- Avoid duplicate type definitions

Examples:

- `material.type.ts`
- `material-form.type.ts`
- `material-create.type.ts`
- `material-table.type.ts`
- `material-filter.type.ts`

---

# 12. Schema to Type Inference

Types should be inferred from schemas when a schema already exists.

Example:

`type MaterialCreateType = z.infer<typeof materialCreateSchema>`

---

# 13. Constants

Location:
features/[feature-name]/constants/

Purpose:
Store **static, immutable values** that are **scoped to a single feature**.

## Allowed Scope

This directory MAY contain ONLY:

- enums
- static labels / text
- keys / identifiers
- static mappings
- feature-specific default values
- feature-local configuration (non-global)

## Examples

- MATERIAL_TABLE_SEARCH_PLACEHOLDER
- MATERIAL_STATUS_LABEL

## Strict Rules

Constants MUST NOT contain:

- any logic
- business logic
- UI logic (rendering rules, conditional UI, responsiveness)
- validation logic
- runtime logic (functions, calculations, Date, Math, env access)
- side effects
- framework or library dependencies (React, Next.js, zod, etc.)

Constants MUST:

- be static and immutable
- be plain values only (primitives, arrays, object literals, enums)
- NOT depend on state, props, environment variables, or execution time

## Global Default Values Rule

DO NOT define **application-wide default values** inside feature constants.

If a value is:

- shared across multiple features
- application-wide
- configurable or environment-dependent

It MUST be defined in:

`config/app.config.ts`

### ❌ Forbidden in Feature Constants

- pagination page size
- pagination max limit
- toast duration
- toast position

### ✅ Correct Location

- pagination.defaultPageSize
- pagination.maxLimit
- toastConfig.duration
- toastConfig.position

## Decision Guide

| Value Type                  | Allowed Location             |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Feature-specific labels     | features/[feature]/constants |
| Feature domain enums        | features/[feature]/constants |
| Global pagination defaults  | config/app.config.ts         |
| Cross-feature configuration | config/app.config.ts         |
| Computed or dynamic values  | ❌ Not allowed               |

## Golden Rule

If a value can change due to **user input, environment, time, or logic**, it is **NOT a constant**.

---

# 14. index.ts

Location:
features/[feature-name]/index.ts

Purpose:
Single public entry point for the feature.

Scope:

- Re-export public API
- Simplify imports
- Hide internal implementation

Example:
`export * from "./actions"`
`export * from "./components"`
`export * from "./constants"`
`export * from "./hooks"`
`export * from "./repositories"`
`export * from "./schemas"`
`export * from "./services"`
`export * from "./table"`
`export * from "./types"`

Usage:
`import { MaterialForm, MaterialCreateAction } from "@/features/materials"`

---

# 15. Data Flow Standard

All features must follow this flow:

`Component/hook → Action → Service → Repository → Prisma Database`

Example flow:

→ MaterialForm  
→ MaterialCreateAction  
→ MaterialCreateService  
→ MaterialCreateRepository  
→ Prisma Database

Rules:

- Actions may call services
- Services may call repositories
- Repositories may call Prisma Database
- Components and hooks must NOT call repositories directly
- Components and hooks may call actions
- Components and hooks may call services

---

# 16. Import and Export Integration

Purpose:
Import and export flows must remain feature-owned and must follow the same feature boundaries as forms, tables, actions, services, repositories, and schemas.

Rules:

- Import and export logic MUST belong to the owning feature
- Feature-specific import and export behavior MUST NOT be implemented in global shared folders
- Import and export UI MAY live in `features/[feature-name]/components/`
- Table-related export triggers and feature-specific export table helpers MAY live in `features/[feature-name]/table/`
- Import and export hooks MAY live in `features/[feature-name]/hooks/`
- Import and export parsers, mappers, transformers, and helper utilities SHOULD live in `features/[feature-name]/lib/`
- Import and export validation schemas MUST live in `features/[feature-name]/schemas/`
- Import and export server entry points MUST live in `features/[feature-name]/actions/`
- Import and export business rules MUST live in `features/[feature-name]/services/`
- Import and export persistence access MUST live in `features/[feature-name]/repositories/` when persistence is required
- Shared import and export helpers MAY be extracted only if they are fully generic and reusable across multiple features
- Raw imported rows MUST NOT be persisted directly without validation and feature-owned mapping
- Exported rows MUST be mapped intentionally and MUST NOT be derived accidentally from arbitrary rendered UI output

Examples:

- `features/materials/components/MaterialImportForm.tsx`
- `features/materials/components/MaterialExportButton.tsx`
- `features/materials/hooks/use-material-import.ts`
- `features/materials/actions/materials-import.action.ts`
- `features/materials/actions/materials-export.action.ts`
- `features/materials/lib/material-import-parser.ts`
- `features/materials/lib/material-export-mapper.ts`
- `features/materials/schemas/material-import.schema.ts`
- `features/materials/table/material-export-columns.ts`

Reference:
Detailed technical rules are defined in:

- `.cursor/rules/export-import/1-data-import-export.mdc`
- `.cursor/rules/export-import/2-csv-export.mdc`
- `.cursor/rules/export-import/3-csv-import.mdc`
